05032nam a22007815i 9780812201437DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112005pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122014377 a10.9783/97808122014372doi  a(DE-B1597)448996  a(OCoLC)979968246  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR448.C52bB74 2005eb 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a820.9/27/090332221 aBrewer, David A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Afterlife of Character, 1726-1825 /cDavid A. Brewer. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b14 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMaterial Texts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tCottagers upon the Textual Commons, an Introduction -- tChapter 1. The Invention of the Fictional Archive -- tChapter 2. Visualization, Theatricality, Fame -- tChapter 3. Character Migration, Detachability, Old Friends -- tChapter 4. Lewd Engraftments and the Richardsonian Coterie Public -- tChapter 5. Shandyism and the Club of True Feelers -- tScott’s Parental Interest, an Afterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Afterlife of Character, 1726-1825 reconstructs how eighteenth-century British readers invented further adventures for beloved characters, including Gulliver, Falstaff, Pamela, and Tristram Shandy. Far from being close-ended and self-contained, the novels and plays in which these characters first appeared were treated by many as merely a starting point, a collective reference perpetually inviting augmentation through an astonishing wealth of unauthorized sequels. Characters became an inexhaustible form of common property, despite their patent authorship. Readers endowed them with value, knowing all the while that others were doing the same and so were collectively forging a new mode of virtual community.By tracing these practices, David A. Brewer shows how the literary canon emerged as much "from below" as out of any of the institutions that have been credited with their invention. Indeed, he reveals the astonishing degree to which authors had to cajole readers into granting them authority over their own creations, authority that seems self-evident to a modern audience.In its innovative methodology and its unprecedented attention to the productive interplay between the audience, the book as a material artifact, and the text as an immaterial entity, The Afterlife of Character, 1726-1825 offers a compelling new approach to eighteenth-century studies, the history of the book, and the very idea of character itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCharacters and characteristics in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aIntellectual propertyzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aIntellectual propertyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 4aCultural Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220143740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812201437423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812201437.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041354-0  Penn Press eBook-Package Literature  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsyl